{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Use British English|date=August 2014}} [[File:Sir Robert Romer 12 December 1891.jpg|right|thumb|''[[Vanity Fair (British magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' caricature, 1891]] '''Sir Robert Romer''', [[Order of the Bath|GCB]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]] (23 December 1840 &ndash; 19 March 1918) was a British judge. He was a [[High Court judge (England and Wales)|High Court judge]] 1890-1899, and a [[Lord Justice of Appeal]] 1899-1906 when he was known as '''Lord Justice Romer'''.
==Biography== Romer was born in [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]], [[Middlesex]].<ref>[https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/35819 Romer, Sir Robert] Oxford Dictionary of National Biography</ref> He attended [[St John's School, Leatherhead]] (in Surrey) and excelled at mathematics at [[Trinity Hall, Cambridge]] where he was [[Senior Wrangler (University of Cambridge)|Senior Wrangler]] in 1863 (the first from Trinity Hall) and was joint winner of [[Smith's Prize]] in that year.<ref>St John's School, Leatherhead. School Register 1852-1904</ref> Following the premature late 1864 death of [[George Boole]], the first professor of maths at Queen's College, Cork, Romer beat out [[Robert Stawell Ball|Robert Ball]] for the vacant position, however he only stayed in Cork for 1865-1866.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/reminiscenceslet00balluoft/reminiscenceslet00balluoft_djvu.txt Reminiscences and Letters of Sir Robert Ball] Edited By W. Vaihntine Ball</ref> He became [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] in 1881, and a bencher of [[Lincoln's Inn]] in 1884.<ref>[http://venn.lib.cam.ac.uk/cgi-bin/search-2016.pl?sur=&suro=w&fir=&firo=c&cit=&cito=c&c=all&z=all&tex=RMR859R&sye=&eye=&col=all&maxcount=50 Robert Romer] ACAD: A Cambridge Alumni Database from 1200 to 1900</ref> The same year he unsuccessfully stood as the Liberal candidate in [[Brighton (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton]].
In 1890 he was appointed [[High Court judge (England and Wales)|High Court judge]] and assigned to the [[Chancery Division]], receiving the customary [[Knight Bachelor|knighthood]]. He served as such until 1899, when he was appointed a [[Lord Justice of Appeal]], in succession to [[Joseph William Chitty|Chitty]]. He resigned in 1906.
Romer was sworn a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Councillor]] in 1899, and elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] in the same year. He was appointed [[Order of the Bath|Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]] (GCB) in the New Year Honours list 1 January 1901,<ref name="GCB">{{London Gazette |issue=27264 |date=8 January 1901 |page=157 }}</ref> and was invested by [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]] in February the same year.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Court Circular |day_of_week=Thursday |date=14 February 1901 |page_number=6 |issue=36378| }}</ref>
He was a member of the Royal Commission on South African Hospitals in 1901, during the [[Boer War]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Royal Commission on South African Hospitals|pmc=2400194 | pages=236–240 | volume=1|issue=2091|journal=British Medical Journal|doi=10.1136/bmj.1.2091.236|year=1901 }}</ref> He was a member of the Royal Commission on University Education in London in 1909.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Thomas Carlyle Parkinson, M.D. (Sydney)|pmc=2318341 | page=574 | volume=1|issue=2513|journal=British Medical Journal|doi=10.1136/bmj.1.2513.574|year=1909 }}</ref>
==Family== In 1864 he married his first cousin Betty Lemon, daughter of his aunt Helen (Nelly) Romer and [[Mark Lemon]], editor of ''[[Punch (magazine)|Punch]]''. Their son was [[Mark Romer, Baron Romer]] and their grandson was [[Charles Romer|Sir Charles Robert Romer]];<ref>[http://www.genealogy.com/forum/surnames/topics/romer/100/ Re: Robert Romer, England, 1860s] genealogy.com</ref> both were also Lords Justice of Appeal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index1769.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-02-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331185148/http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index1769.htm |archivedate=31 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Their daughter Helen Mary married future [[Lord Chancellor]] [[Frederic Maugham, 1st Viscount Maugham|Frederic Maugham]].
